ionary who served in Smyrna, Egypt, and Jerusalem under the American Board of Commissioners for Foreign Missions before his 1825 death in Beirut."}],"education":[{"school_name":"Washington County Grammar School","dates":"1837","type":"secondary","notes":"Montpelier VT — entered Fall 1837 after farm childhood."},{"institution_id":"INST058","school_name":"Dartmouth College","dates":"1843","type":"undergraduate","notes":"A.B. 1843."},{"school_name":"Bangor Theological Seminary","dates":"1843-1846","type":"theological","notes":"Three-year ministerial training course. Graduated 1846."}],"career":[{"role":"Pastor","organization":"Congregational Church (Richmond ME)","start_year":1847,"end_year":1856,"notes":"Ordained January 14, 1847. Nine-year pastorate."},{"role":"Pastor","organization":"Congregational Church (Williamstown VT)","start_year":1856,"notes":"Settled minister Williamstown VT after Maine."},{"role":"Pastor","organization":"Congregational Churches (Westhampton MA, Westminster VT, Wendell MA, Dummerston VT)","end_year":1890,"notes":"Itinerant settled pastorates plus various supply work. Settled Westminster VT 1890."},{"role":"Clerk and assistant","organization":"Congregational Church (Westminster VT)","start_year":1890,"end_year":1908,"notes":"Active in church through retirement."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST058","relationship":"alumnus"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"pliny-barnard-1820"},"TD0128":{"id":"TD0128","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"display_name":"Julia Hobart Barnard","first_name":"Julia","last_name":"Barnard","maiden_name":"Hobart","married_names":["Barnard"],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777669167/juliabarnard_mngkch.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary.","bio_blurb":"Minister’s wife who raised seven on the frontier"},"birth":{"year":1819,"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1908,"city":"Westminster","county":"Windham","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"residence":{},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM178","plot_notes":"Westminster New Cemetery, Westminster VT — alongside Pliny."},"gender":"female","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_john_talcott":8,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{"father_id":"X02368","mother_id":"TD0120"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X02369","date_year":1846,"date_month":11,"date_day":4,"location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1908,"children_ids":["TD0234","TD0235","TD0233"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":[],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"FindAGrave — Julia Hobart Barnard","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/185551300/julia-barnard"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Mother of seven during itinerant pastorate","body":"Julia raised her seven children across her husband Pliny's wandering pastorates — Richmond Maine, Williamstown Vermont, Waitsfield Vermont, Westhampton Massachusetts, Westminster Vermont, Wendell Massachusetts, Dummerston Vermont. Their daughter Alice Theresa died of diphtheria at fifteen in 1866; the others reached adulthood and scattered across Vermont, New Hampshire, and Michigan."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married one week, then off to the frontier","body":"She wed her minister husband and a week later set out with him for his pastorate in the Maine backcountry. They raised seven children there and across Vermont — and buried one daughter, dead of diphtheria at fifteen."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[],"career":[],"military_service":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"slug":"julia-barnard-1819"},"X02368":{"id":"X02368","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"bio":{"display_name":"Rev. James Hobart","first_name":"James","last_name":"Hobart","title":"Reverend","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777668484/revjameshobart_drsmyx.png","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"birth":{"year":1766,"month":8,"day":2,"city":"Plymouth","county":"Grafton","state":"New Hampshire","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1862,"month":7,"day":16,"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"Berlin","county":"Washington","state":"Vermont","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM176","plot_notes":"Berlin Corner Cemetery, Berlin Corners VT — alongside Betsey."},"gender":"male","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0},"parents":{},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"TD0120","date_year":1804,"date_month":8,"date_day":30,"location_city":"Berlin","location_state":"Vermont","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_self","end_year":1862,"children_ids":["TD0121","TD0122","TD0123","TD0124","TD0125","TD0126","TD0127","TD0128","TD0129","TD0130","TD0131","TD0132"]}],"number_of_marriages":1,"tags":["minister","clergy","extraordinary_longevity"],"research_tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"Vermont Genealogy — Biography of Rev. James Hobart","url":"https://vermontgenealogy.com/washington/biography-of-rev-james-hobart.htm"},{"label":"FindAGrave — Rev James Hobart","url":"https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/641556/james-hobart"}],"research_sources":[],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"religion","header":"Berlin Vermont's first settled minister thirty-one years","body":"Ordained November 7, 1798 as Berlin Congregational's first settled minister, James drafted the church's confession of faith, covenant, and articles of discipline himself. His 31-year pastorate ran to May 1829, when a mutual council dismissed him. He then spent twelve years preaching in New Hampshire and twenty more itinerating around Worcester, Berlin, and West Berlin Vermont."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"Walked six miles and preached at ninety-five","body":"Per his obituary, 'in the very last year of his life, his 96th, he was able to preach a pretty well connected discourse, and could walk 6 or 8 miles in a day.' Below ordinary height with erect carriage, great memory, and a strong distinct voice, James was described as 'self-denying, laborious and persevering, having quite a missionary spirit.'"},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Three daughters married Congregational ministers","body":"Three of James and Betsey's daughters married Congregational ministers across New England: Pamelia married Rev. Rufus Child (Gilmanton NH then Berlin), Julia married Rev. Pliny Fisk Barnard (Richmond ME then Williamstown VT then Westminster VT), and Hannah married Rev. George Craven (Methodist, Danville VT). The Berlin pulpit's reach extended through the next generation."},{"number":4,"category":"religion","header":"Walked six miles a day preaching at ninety-six","body":"In the ninety-sixth year of his life Rev. Hobart preached well-connected discourses and was able to walk six or eight miles in a day. Below average height, he stood erect and was blessed with a retentive memory, strong voice, and good delivery."}],"cross_connections":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"education":[{"institutio